Notes: Parasitic, gastrointestinal. For Eimeriidae. On WoRMS, Chromista (Kingdom) Harosa (Subkingdom) Alveolata (Infrakingdom) Myzozoa (Phylum) Apicomplexa (Subphylum) Sporozoa (Infraphylum) Conoidasida (Class) Coccidiasina (Subclass) Eucoccidiorida (Order) Eimeriorina (Suborder) Eimeriidae (Family)
Coral-infesting parasites. On NCBI, Lineage( full ) cellular organisms; Eukaryota; Sar; Alveolata; Apicomplexa; Conoidasida; Corallicolida
Symbiont location: Detected in mesenteries in the gastric cavity of polyps
Symbiont Specialization: Second most abundant symbiont of corals after dinoflagellate photosymbionts
Presence in other subeuphotic regions?: Found in some deep-sea corals in depths below the photic zone.
Presence in extreme environment?: Detected in mesenteries in the gastric cavity of polyps. Some of its closest relatives were recovered from anoxic marine sediment from Greenland. Suggests that corallicolids may occupy a microoxic niche in corals.
Field-based studies: Research has shown that the corallicolids have a minor impact on host (coral) fitness under normal circumstances, but increase in abundance and impact on host when corals are stressed. Such as if a coral were affected by "white plague" disease. Corallicolid plasts likely not involved in photosynthesis, though LIPOR genes may still be producing chlorophyll.
Sequencing: Vohsen et al. 2020. Deep-sea corals provide new insight into the ecology, evolution, and the role of plastids in widespread apicomplexan symbionts of anthozoans. Microbiome 8, 34 (2020). https://doi.org/10.1186/s40168-020-00798-w;Trznadel, Morelia, et al. "Coral-Infecting Parasites in Cold Marine Ecosystems." Available at SSRN 4657711.
